## Definition

A **closure** is a function that retains access to variables from its **outer (enclosing) lexical scope** even after that outer function has returned.

```js
function makeCounter() {
  let count = 0;
  return function increment() {
    count++;
    return count;
  };
}

const counter = makeCounter();
console.log(counter()); // 1
console.log(counter()); // 2
```

Here `increment` closes over `count`. Every call to `makeCounter` creates a **new, independent** closure with its own `count`.

## Common uses
- **Data privacy / encapsulation** — hide state that should not be directly accessible.
- **Factory / partial application** — pre-configure functions with specific arguments.
- **Module pattern** — expose a public API while keeping internals private.
- **Event handlers / callbacks** — capture loop variables or component state.

## Classic gotcha (var in loops)

```js
// Bug: all click handlers print 3
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  btn[i].onclick = () => console.log(i);
}
// Fix: use let (block-scoped) or an IIFE
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  btn[i].onclick = () => console.log(i); // 0, 1, 2
}
```

## Promises

A **Promise** is an object representing an eventual value. It is in one of three states: *pending*, *fulfilled*, or *rejected*.

```js
fetch('/api/user')
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
```

## async / await

`async/await` is **syntactic sugar** over Promises. An `async` function always returns a Promise; `await` pauses execution inside that function until the awaited Promise settles.

```js
async function getUser() {
  try {
    const res = await fetch('/api/user');
    const data = await res.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
  }
}
```

## When to use which

- Use **`async/await`** for sequential async steps — reads like synchronous code, easier to debug.
- Use **Promise combinators** (`Promise.all`, `Promise.allSettled`, `Promise.race`) when you need to run multiple async operations **in parallel**.

```js
// Parallel with async/await
const [users, posts] = await Promise.all([getUsers(), getPosts()]);
```

**Error handling:** `try/catch` with `await`, or `.catch()` with raw Promises — both work; be consistent.

## Prototype Chain

Every JavaScript object has an internal `[[Prototype]]` link pointing to another object (or `null`). When you access a property, JS traverses this chain until it finds the property or reaches `null`.

```js
const animal = { breathes: true };
const dog = Object.create(animal);
dog.legs = 4;

console.log(dog.breathes); // true  — found on prototype
console.log(dog.legs);     // 4     — found on dog itself
```

## Constructor Functions & `prototype`

Functions have a `.prototype` property. Objects created via `new Fn()` have `[[Prototype]]` set to `Fn.prototype`.

```js
function Animal(name) { this.name = name; }
Animal.prototype.speak = function() { return `${this.name} makes a sound`; };

const cat = new Animal('Cat');
console.log(cat.speak()); // Cat makes a sound
```

## ES6 Classes

`class` is **syntactic sugar** over prototype-based inheritance:

```js
class Animal {
  constructor(name) { this.name = name; }
  speak() { return `${this.name} makes a sound`; }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  speak() { return `${this.name} barks`; }
}
```

`extends` sets up the prototype chain; `super()` calls the parent constructor. Under the hood it is still prototypal.

## Debounce

Delays execution until **a pause in events** of at least `delay` ms. Each new event resets the timer. The callback fires once **after** the burst ends.

```js
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timer;
  return (...args) => {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn(...args), delay);
  };
}

// Fire search only after user stops typing for 300 ms
input.addEventListener('input', debounce(search, 300));
```

**Use when:** search-as-you-type, form validation, window resize handlers (fire once when done).

## Throttle

Guarantees the callback fires **at most once per `limit` ms**, regardless of how many events occur.

```js
function throttle(fn, limit) {
  let inThrottle;
  return (...args) => {
    if (!inThrottle) {
      fn(...args);
      inThrottle = true;
      setTimeout(() => (inThrottle = false), limit);
    }
  };
}

// Update position at most every 16 ms (~60 fps)
window.addEventListener('scroll', throttle(updatePosition, 16));
```

**Use when:** scroll/mousemove handlers, rate-limiting API calls, game loops.

## Summary

| | Debounce | Throttle |
|-|----------|----------|
| Fires | After silence | At regular intervals |
| Good for | Final value needed | Steady feedback needed |

## How Events Bubble

When an event fires on a child element, it **bubbles up** through all ancestor elements. Event delegation exploits this by placing a **single listener on a parent** instead of many listeners on children.

```js
// Without delegation — one listener per item
document.querySelectorAll('li').forEach(li =>
  li.addEventListener('click', handleClick)
);

// With delegation — one listener on the parent
document.querySelector('ul').addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  if (e.target.matches('li')) {
    handleClick(e.target);
  }
});
```

## Benefits

1. **Performance** — fewer listeners = less memory.
2. **Dynamic elements** — works automatically for items added to the DOM after the listener is attached.
3. **Simpler cleanup** — remove one listener instead of many.

## Key properties

- `e.target` — element that triggered the event.
- `e.currentTarget` — element the listener is attached to.
- `e.stopPropagation()` — prevents further bubbling.
- `e.preventDefault()` — cancels the default browser action.

## Component

A **component** is a reusable, self-contained piece of UI — a JavaScript function (or class) that accepts inputs and returns JSX.

```jsx
function Greeting({ name }) {
  return <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;
}
```

## Props

**Props** (properties) are inputs passed **from parent to child**. They are **read-only** inside the component — a component must never mutate its own props.

```jsx
<Greeting name="Alice" />
// Inside Greeting, props.name === 'Alice'
```

## State

**State** is data **owned and managed by the component itself**. Changing state triggers a re-render.

```jsx
function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);
  return (
    <button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>
      Clicked {count} times
    </button>
  );
}
```

## Key distinctions

| | Props | State |
|-|-------|-------|
| Owner | Parent | Component itself |
| Mutable by component? | No | Yes (via setter) |
| Triggers re-render? | Yes (when parent re-renders) | Yes (on change) |
| Source of truth | Parent | Component |

**Lifting state up:** when two sibling components need shared data, move state to their closest common ancestor and pass it down as props.

## useState

`useState` adds local state to a functional component. It returns a **[value, setter]** pair. Calling the setter schedules a re-render with the new value.

```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

// Functional update (safe when new state depends on old)
setCount(prev => prev + 1);
```

## useEffect

`useEffect` handles **side effects** (data fetching, subscriptions, DOM mutations) after render.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => tick(), 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(id); // cleanup on unmount / re-run
}, [/* dependencies */]);
```

**Dependency array:**
- `[]` — run once after mount.
- `[a, b]` — run when `a` or `b` changes.
- omitted — run after every render (usually a bug).

## Rules of Hooks

1. **Only call hooks at the top level** — never inside loops, conditions, or nested functions. React relies on the **call order** being consistent across renders.
2. **Only call hooks from React function components or custom hooks** — not regular JS functions.

These rules exist because React uses the order of hook calls to associate state and effects with a component. The ESLint plugin `eslint-plugin-react-hooks` enforces both rules automatically.

## Controlled Input

The input value is **driven by React state**. The component is the single source of truth; every keystroke triggers a state update which re-renders the input.

```jsx
function Form() {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState('');

  return (
    <input
      type="email"
      value={email}
      onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}
```

**Advantages:** you can validate on every keystroke, format/mask input, conditionally disable the submit button based on value.

## Uncontrolled Input

The DOM manages its own value. You read it via a **ref** (typically at submit time).

```jsx
function Form() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  function handleSubmit() {
    console.log(inputRef.current.value);
  }

  return <input type="text" ref={inputRef} defaultValue="initial" />;
}
```

**Advantages:** less boilerplate, integrates more easily with non-React code, can be faster for large forms.

## When to use each

| Situation | Recommendation |
|-----------|----------------|
| Real-time validation / formatting | Controlled |
| Simple form, only need value on submit | Uncontrolled |
| Integrating third-party DOM library | Uncontrolled |
| Complex form logic | Controlled or `react-hook-form` |

**React Hook Form** uses uncontrolled inputs internally for performance but exposes a controlled-like API.

## Prevent Unnecessary Re-renders

**`React.memo`** — memoizes a functional component; re-renders only when props change by reference.

```jsx
const UserCard = React.memo(({ user }) => <div>{user.name}</div>);
```

**`useMemo`** — memoizes an expensive computed value.
```jsx
const sorted = useMemo(() => items.sort(fn), [items]);
```

**`useCallback`** — memoizes a callback so its reference is stable across renders (important when passing to `memo`-wrapped children).
```jsx
const handleClick = useCallback(() => doSomething(id), [id]);
```

## Code Splitting

```jsx
const Chart = React.lazy(() => import('./Chart'));

function Dashboard() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
      <Chart />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

Loads `Chart` only when rendered, reducing the initial bundle.

## Other techniques

- **Virtualization** (`react-window`, `TanStack Virtual`) — render only visible rows in long lists.
- **Avoid anonymous functions/objects in JSX** — they create new references every render, defeating `memo`.
- **State colocation** — keep state close to where it is used to minimize the re-render surface.
- **React 18 transitions** — `useTransition` marks slow updates as non-urgent to keep input responsive.
